# Android App Rules

## Stack

- Kotlin, Jetpack Compose for UI, Room for local DB, OkHttp for HTTP
- Google Nearby Connections API for peer-to-peer transport
- Google Tink for cryptographic signature verification
- Foreground Service for always-on relay behavior

## Code Style

- Use Kotlin idioms: `val` over `var`, data classes for models, `when` over `if-else` chains.
- Coroutines for all async work. Use `Dispatchers.IO` for disk/network, `Dispatchers.Main` for UI.
- Name ViewModels as `<Screen>ViewModel`. Name composables as `<Screen>Screen`.
- Keep composable functions small. Extract reusable components into separate files.

## Architecture

- MVVM: ViewModel holds state, Composables render it, Repository handles data.
- Room entities go in a `data/` package. ViewModels in `ui/`. Services in `service/`.
- Do not put business logic in Composables. Logic belongs in ViewModel or Repository.

## Nearby Connections

- Service ID: `"com.wake.dtn"`
- Use `Strategy.P2P_CLUSTER` for multi-peer mesh topology.
- Connection callbacks go in a dedicated `NearbyConnectionManager` class, not scattered in Activities.
- Always disconnect after bundle exchange completes. Do not hold connections open.

## Permissions

Required at runtime: `ACCESS_FINE_LOCATION`, `BLUETOOTH_SCAN`, `BLUETOOTH_ADVERTISE`, `BLUETOOTH_CONNECT`, `NEARBY_WIFI_DEVICES` (Android 13+), `POST_NOTIFICATIONS` (Android 13+).

## Bundle Storage

- Payload bytes stored as files in `context.filesDir`, metadata in Room.
- File naming: `{query_id}_{chunk_index}.bundle`
- Eviction: TTL-expired first, then LRU when storage exceeds 500 MB cap.
